INSERT INTO artesania (catArte, idioma, descrArte) VALUES ('bordado','en','Serrano embroidery was used in textiles for the home, in popular clothing or in ritual cloths and altar cloths, among other things. The animals, mythological or real (griffins and dragons and the occasional cockerel, butterfly, wild boar, owl or dog), are interwoven with plants, including the tree of life.');
INSERT INTO artesania (catArte, idioma, descrArte) VALUES ('bordado','en','Each animal represented has a meaning, for example, the two-headed eagle represents marriage; the lion, virility; the one-headed bird, womanhood; the heart from which the flower emerges, love; the tree of life, health and longevity, and so on.');
INSERT INTO artesania (catArte, idioma, descrArte) VALUES ('bordado','en','Other features of Serrano embroidery are the absence of human figures and geometric motifs, suggesting the influence of ancient oriental, Renaissance and Moorish civilisations. Another interesting fact is the language of the colours used: blue was used to shroud the deceased, while red was embroidered on the bedclothes of newlyweds. In the mid-20th century, new colours were incorporated: mauve, purple, grass green, cobalt blue, salmon, among others.');
INSERT INTO artesania (catArte, idioma, descrArte) VALUES ('bordado','en','The basic materials for embroidery were linen and wool. Over the years, these were replaced by silk thread, and later came cotton which, together with silk, has survived to the present day. Until the 19th century, handlooms were used to weave the fabrics, using the mixed technique of counted and drawn threads. Once they disappeared, industrial weaving with other fibres began to be used.');
